  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalizes financial transactions designed to conceal the source of illegal funds\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishes reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Imposes civil and criminal penalties for violations\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Loss of business licenses\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Follows Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Collaborates with international law enforcement agencies\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income and to track potential financial crimes.",
